value.value: Steps required to transform an immature secretory vesicle into a mature secretory vesicle. Typically proceeds through homotypic membrane fusion and membrane remodeling.
A chromatin silencing complex that binds and bridges separate nucleosomal histones resulting in heterochromatin assembly and chromatin looping.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of conidium over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Conidia are non-motile spores produced via mitotic asexual reproduction in higher fungi; they are haploid cells genetically identical to their haploid parent. They are produced by conversion of hyphal elements, or are borne on sporogenous cells on or within specialized structures termed conidiophores, and participate in dispersal of the fungus.
Any process that reduces the pH of the Golgi lumen, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.

label.value: membrane addition at site of mitotic cytokinesis

value.value: A mitotic cell cycle process involved in the net addition of membrane at the site of cytokinesis; includes vesicle recruitment and fusion, local lipid synthesis and insertion.
A gated channel activity that enables the transmembrane transfer of a chloride ion by a channel that opens in response to a change in pH.
Catalysis of the reaction: GTP=(8S)-3',8-cyclo-7,8-dihydroguanosine 5'-triphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: (8S)-3',8-cyclo-7,8-dihydroguanosine 5'-triphosphate = cyclic pyranopterin phosphate + diphosphate.
A supramolecular fiber formed from fibronectin molecules. The fibrils are 5 to 25nm in diameter and can form branched meshworks.
A laminin complex composed of alpha3B, beta3 and gamma2 polypeptide chains.
The region that lies just beneath the plasma membrane in the part of a cell that is closest to the anterior as defined by the developing, or existing, anterior/posterior axis.
The region that lies just beneath the plasma membrane in the part of a cell that is closest to the posterior as defined by the developing, or existing, anterior/posterior axis.
The cell cycle process in which the distance is lengthened between poles of the mitotic spindle during mitotic prophase.
The cell cycle process in which the distance is lengthened between poles of the mitotic spindle during mitotic anaphase B.

label.value: regulation of DNA recombination at centromere

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of DNA recombination within centromeric DNA.

label.value: positive regulation of DNA recombination at centromere

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA recombination at the centromere.

label.value: negative regulation of DNA recombination at centromere

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of genetic recombination at the centromere.
Catalysis of the reaction: NAD+ + H2O = nicotinamide + ADP-ribose, in a two steps reaction: first an ADP-ribosyl cyclase reaction, followed by a cyclic ADP-ribose hydrolase reaction.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of ubiquitin units from Met1-linked (or linear) polyubiquitin chains.
The selective degradation of proteasomes by macroautophagy.
The attachment of an endoplasmic reticulum membrane to the plasma membrane via molecular tethers.
The process of assisting in the folding of tRNAs into the correct tertiary structure.

A telomere maintenance process that results in the formation of small fragments of circular extrachromosomal DNA elements which contain telomeric DNA. It is speculated that telomeric DNA-containing double minutes are formed through a recombination event between the telomere and chromosome-internal TTAGGG-like sequences. Telomeric DNA-containing double minutes appear as two closely positioned dots in metaphase.

A telomere loop disassembly process that results in the disassembly of telomeric D-loops. A telomeric D-loop is a three-stranded DNA displacement loop that forms at the site where the telomeric 3' single-stranded DNA overhang (formed of the repeat sequence TTAGGG in mammals) is tucked back inside the double-stranded component of telomeric DNA molecule, thus forming a t-loop or telomeric-loop and protecting the chromosome terminus.

Binding to a telomeric D-loop. A telomeric D-loop is a three-stranded DNA displacement loop that forms at the site where the telomeric 3' single-stranded DNA overhang (formed of the repeat sequence TTAGGG in mammals) is tucked back inside the double-stranded component of telomeric DNA molecule, thus forming a t-loop or telomeric-loop and protecting the chromosome terminus.

An intracellular compartmentalized cilium structure found in insect spermatids which is bounded by a membrane derived from the invagination of the cell membrane that remains associated with the primary cilium as it is internalized. The ciliary cap is maintained at the end of the axoneme distal to the centriole and is separated from the cytosolic axoneme/cytoplasm by a putative transition zone, which may extend into the ciliary cap, and include a structure at the base of the ciliary cap termed the ring centriole.

A ring-like structure observed at the base of the ciliary cap of insect spermatids. This structure may anchor the axoneme to the ciliary cap membrane and/or act as a diffusion barrier, proposed to be analogous to the annulus of mammalian sperm flagellum.

The process in which an axoneme is exposed entirely or partially to the cytoplasm or by which the cytoplasmic portion is assembled or extended. Cytosolic ciliogenesis can occur following compartmentalized ciliogenesis, in which the cilium is formed within a compartment separated from the cytoplasm.
The F-actin-rich core of an adhesion structure characterized by formation upon cell substrate contact and localization at the substrate-attached part of the cell.
The ring structure surrounding the podosome core, containing proteins such as vinculin and talin.
The part of the late spermatid or spermatozoon that contains the nucleus and acrosome.
Actin-based structures involved in establishing close contact between mature spermatids and Sertoli cells at the luminal end of the Sertoli cell.
Actin-based structures involved in establishing the blood-testis barrier of the Sertoli cell.
The concave part of the late spermatid head or spermatozoon head that forms the ventral portion of the head, particularly in some rodent species.
Testis-specific junction between mature spermatids and Sertoli cells at the luminal end of the Sertoli cell.
Testis-specific junction between mature Sertoli cells involved in establishing the blood-testis barrier of the Sertoli cell.

label.value: protein localization to tricellular tight junction

value.value: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a tricellular tight junction.
The part of an actin filament where the structure forks.
The surface of a migrating cell that is in contact with the substratum or cell layer.
A macromolecular fiber consisting of actin and cofilin that is formed in the nucleus as a consequence of chemical or mechanical stress conditions.

Any protein maturation process achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond or bonds within a neuropeptide precursor. Processing leads to the attainment of the full functional capacity of the neuropeptide.
A histone-variant containing protein complex which forms a centromere specific nucleosome-like structure, involved in centromeric chromatin organization.

label.value: high-affinity ferrous iron transmembrane transporter activity

value.value: Enables the transfer of ferrous iron (Fe(II) or Fe2+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other. In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.
A protein complex which transports ferrous iron (Fe(III) or Fe3+) ions from the vacuole, the main storage component of intracellular free iron, into the cytoplasm in a low iron environment.

definition.value: An example of this is FET5 in Saccharomyces cerevisiae (P43561) in PMID:9413439.

value.value: Any process in which the microtubule organizing center is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.

The tissue remodeling process by which the Sertoli cell barrier is temporarily disrupted and reorganized to accommodate the transit of preleptotene spermatocytes at stage VIII of the epithelial cycle.

label.value: antimicrobial humoral immune response mediated by antimicrobial peptide

value.value: An immune response against microbes mediated by anti-microbial peptides in body fluid.
The location where a secondary projection arises from a neuron projection.
The region of the neuronal cytoplasm located in dendritic spines.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cholecystokinin stimulus.
